<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Criticizes Premier </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1001134194 Tallinn BNS in English 1059 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1001134194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 10, BNS -- The chairman of the 
opposition Coalition Party, Tiit Vahi, accused Prime Minister 
Mart Laar of failure to cope with his duties and said it was the 
head of the government rather than the Cabinet as such that 
needed replacement. 
  "Our (the Coalition Party's -- BNS) position is that the 
head 
of government is failing to cope with his tasks," Vahi said. 
Vahi, the predecessor of Mart Laar in the prime minister's 
office, said his party would be ready for cooperation if the 
opportunity came up to appoint a new prime minister candidate. 
  Vahi said there was no constitutional crisis in Estonia, as 
the constitution gives the president the right to sack ministers 
and approve new ministers into office. 
  "How the authors of the constitution meant it, is quite 
another thing," Vahi said. 
  But the Coalition Party leader also added he had been 
somewhat bewildered by the president's decision not to relieve 
the economics minister of office. 
  "In my personal opinion, this can be interpreted as the 
president's wish to shape the setup of Mart Laar's Cabinet," he 
said. 
  Vahi added that the interior political crisis emerged in 
Estonia had to be resolved by intensive negotiations between the 
prime minister and the president. 

</TEXT>

