<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Meri Accepting Proposals </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101102894 Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network in Estonian 0900 
GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101102894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Estonian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Lennart Meri signed today, in front of the 
Riigikogu, the proposals by Prime Minister Mart Laar, so to 
speak, concerning the government reshuffle. 
  In his speech, the president emphasized it was not what one 
would wish, but it was compelled by this moment in the internal 
and external political situation. In the words of Meri, an 
exceedingly unsuitable time has been chosen for the government 
reshuffle, because leading Estonian politicians should, at 
present, give the main attention to the NATO and the U.S.-Russia 
summit meetings, and not to the examination of, so to speak, 
one's own navel. 
  The president regards the wish by the Isamaa [Fatherland 
faction] to stay in power at any cost as the cause of the 
situation that has arisen. The president expressed surprise 
that Laar himself did not resign, but began a government 
reshuffle. The resignation of Laar, in the opinion of Lennart 
Meri, is in the interests of Isamaa itself. The Isamaa crisis 
is a crisis for the prime minister. Meri appealed also for a 
decisive expansion of the government coalition. 
  With that, the president has officially released Toomas 
Sildmae from the position as economy minister, and appointed 
Heiki Kranich and Toivo Jurgenson as finance and economy 
ministers respectively. 

</TEXT>

