<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security To `Pay Attention' to Foreign Parties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1101105894 Tallinn BNS in English 1805 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1101105894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Jan 10, BNS -- The Defense Police at 
present has got no reasons to initiate criminal proceedings 
against Pyotr Rozhok, a representative of Vladimir Zhirinovsky's 
Russian Liberal Democratic Party in Estonia, the head of the 
country's security police said. 
  Juri Pihl, the director general of the Defense Police 
Department, added that Estonia still needed "to keep an eye on 
such people." He said this was necessary despite the fact that 
the country's authorities knew of nothing Rozhok or his fellow 
Russian Liberal Democratic Party supporters had done against 
Estonia's national interests. 
  Rozhok a few days earlier told the press a branch of 
Zhirinovsky's party existed in Estonia. 
  Estonian Justice Minister Kaido Kama has called the party's 
alleged activity in Estonia illegal, because the branch 
organization has not been formally registered with the country's 
authorities. Kama said the activity of the Zhirinosky group in 
Estonia should be investigated by the defense police. 
  Also President Lennart Meri in a speech recently said the 
country's security police had to pay attention to the activity 
of "some foreign political parties in Estonia." 
  Rozhok, a resident of the northeastern town of Narva, claims 
his telephone is being tapped, but says he has had no direct 
contacts with Estonian defense police officials so far. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

