<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Decision Not To Affect Relations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001170694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1618 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001170694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature] </F>
  [Text] The lack of a "too sensitive reaction" from Russia 
and other countries to Lithuania's decision to join NATO proves 
that this step is in line with the processes taking place in 
real life, said President Algirdas Brazauskas on Monday [10 
January]. 
  Addressing a press conference in Vilnius, he said he hopes 
that a resolution concerning the prospects for integrating 
Lithuania and other countries of Eastern and Central Europe into 
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization will be adopted at the 
NATO summit taking place in Brussels. 
  Brazauskas believes that the implementation of the 
"partnership for peace" initiative, designed to pave the way for 
the countries in Central and Eastern Europe to membership in the 
continent's collective security structures, will be conducive to 
this. 
  According to the president, there is a need to search for 
solutions that would make it possible to include the whole of 
Europe in a system of collective security. 
  Brazauskas told his hosts at the National Radio's Russian 
Service in Vilnius over the weekend that Lithuania's decision to 
integrate into NATO must not change its relations with Russia 
and other neighbors in any way. 
  In his words, this political move "should not be interpreted 
as an intention to "alter or stiffen ties with Russia and other 
states." All European leaders, in his opinion, should agree on 
"a single security umbrella." 
  Prime Minister Adolfas Slezevicius, accompanying Brazauskas, 
added that "Lithuania's pro-western orientation is nothing new 
in its foreign policy". According to him, integration with NATO 
and other European security structures will be conducive to 
regional stability, indispensable not only to Lithuania but to 
all neighboring states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55687 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov007_v_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-007 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Foreign Minister Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001172394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1613 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001172394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature] </F>
  [Text] Lithuania does not believe that it committed "an 
unfriendly act" toward Russia by expressing its desire to join 
NATO, Deputy Foreign Minister Albinas Januska told Interfax on 
Monday [10 January]. 
  In his opinion, he said, a number of views expressed by the 
Russian president's press secretary, Vyacheslav Kostikov, and by 
Russia's Foreign Ministry recently "look odd." However on the 
whole, Januska said, Moscow's reaction to the letter sent by the 
Lithuanian authorities to NATO, with the request to consider the 
possibility of admitting Lithuania to the North Atlantic Treaty 
Organization, "is quite natural for Russia," and it "testifies 
to some vestiges of the past in Russian thinking." According to 
him, even the highest echelons of power in Russia evidently have 
not completely shed their notion of NATO as a "hostile bloc." 
  Lithuania's decision to become a member of the North 
Atlantic 
Treaty Organization was prompted by the circumstance that the 
country "is not in a position to ensure full security for itself 
on its own," the deputy foreign minister explained. "We view 
NATO as the only guarantor of stability and security in Europe, 
and therefore we appeal to that organization," he said. 
  "The strengthening of nationalist and expansionist forces in 
Russian politics gave rise to some anxiety" in Lithuania, the 
diplomat said. "To some extent, this is what prompted us to 
search for other means to ensure our security, but our striving 
(to join NATO - IF note) must not be explained only with this," 
he noted. 
  According to Januska, sometimes Moscow tries to pretend that 
the desire of Russia's neighbor countries to join NATO provides 
the nationalist forces in Russia itself with trump cards. "If 
we continue to be in fear of aggravating frictions within 
Russia, we simply will not be able to uphold our own interests," 
he said. 
  Lithuania is prepared to cooperate with the Russian 
Federation within the framework of the "partnership for peace" 
concept worked out by NATO, the deputy foreign minister said. 
He added, however, that Lithuania's ultimate goal is to be a 
"full-fledged member" of that organization. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

