<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Citizens Granted Right To Carry Firearms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101120694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1132 
GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101120694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladas Burbulis] </F>
  [Text] Vilnius, 11 Jan -- The Lithuanian Seimas today 
ratified a law permitting citizens of the republic to acquire 
and carry light firearms. The new law comes into force on 1 
April this year, although, as one of the Seimas members joked, 
"1 April is not the most appropriate date." 
  Firearms may be legally acquired by persons over the age of 
25 who have no court record, do not abuse spirits, are 
well-balanced, not addicted to drugs, and who are not registered 
at a psychiatric clinic. 
  It was pointed out at the Seimas session, that the adoption 
of such a law was a forced measure, since the rise in crime in 
Lithuania is getting beyond state control. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

