<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament To Discuss `Little Constitution' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1101112194 Tallinn BNS in English 1805 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1101112194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 10, BNS -- During its spring session, 
the Lithuanian parliament is scheduled to discuss laws dealing 
with reforms in local administration and the country's 
administrative-territorial division. The whole package has been 
tagged "the little Constitution" of Lithuania. 
  The Lithuanian president, lawmakers government members, 
municipal officials and regional government commissioners met in 
the parliament Monday [10 January] to discuss the principles of 
local administration and territorial division reforms. 
  The meeting's participants discussed several issues, 
including a new administrative-territorial division of 
Lithuania, municipal property problems and a bill on municipal 
elections. 
  Municipal elections in Lithuania are scheduled for next 
fall. 
The draft provides for a single-mandate system of elections, but 
several members of the ruling Lithuanian Democratic Labor Party 
faction proposed to introduce proportional representation. 
  Opposition MP [member of parliament] Andrius Kubilius said 
Monday the opposition will only back a single-mandate system. 

</TEXT>

