<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Discounts Gamsakhurdia Threat </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001131294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1136 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001131294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze said that the 
former president Zviad Gamsakhurdia, who killed himself 
recently, "did not represent a serious political force in 
today's Georgia because his ideology and his supporters had been 
defeated." 
  Shevardnadze warned against complacency, however. In his 
words, there have been certain groups behind Gamsakhurdia which 
"will try again to set up a pro-fascist organization which will 
oppose the existing authorities." 
  Shevardnadze believes that it was up to Gamsakhurdia's 
family 
where to bury him. "We will agree to anything," he said. 
  He called for an international investigation of 
Gamsakhurdia's death "to prevent any rumors." 

</TEXT>

