<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Duma Disputes Composition of Factions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101121494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1157 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101121494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 11 TASS -- State Duma, the low 
chamber of the Russian Federal Assembly (legislature) is now 
engaged in a heated debate about how many people can form a 
parliamentary group or faction. No decision was reached before 
the lunch break. Three figures were proposed -- 14, 20 and 50 
people. A rating vote left only the last two numbers for 
further debate, but none scored a majority in further voting. 
  Factions, their leaders and numbers are of special concern 
to 
the present legislature in which the Liberal Democratic Party 
can command the largest single group of deputies and thus have a 
decisive say in voting. 
  Before the break the Duma elected members of the commission 
charged with seeing to it that the electronic system used in 
registering and displaying voting results function effectively, 
and two other commissions. The deputies also elected a 
provisional secretariat of the State Duma. 

</TEXT>

