<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Communists Not To Seek Post of Duma Speaker </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001161194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1542 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001161194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Aleksandrova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 10 TASS -- The leaders of major 
Russian parliament factions have not adopted the final decision 
on the candidate to the post of the State Duma speaker, but 
succeeded in "working out the concept of approach to this 
issue," Viktor Zerkaltsev, a communist lawmaker told ITAR-TASS. 
  He said the factions have decided not to disclose the 
preliminary agreements on this issue, but did not deny that the 
Communist Party would not claim the speaker's post as "it does 
not consider itself to be a small faction". 
  The leaders of the four biggest factions agreed that the 
post 
of the speaker should be occupied by the representative of "a 
neutral small faction" while all the big factions will get the 
posts of deputy speakers, according to a statement made by 
Vladimir Zhirinovskiy, leader of the Russian Liberal Democratic 
Party. But on January 7 leaders of the Russia's Choice bloc 
abandoned the talks on the question. 
  Zerkaltsev regards this decision of the Russia's Choice bloc 
as "surprising". Until recently the bloc "though not accepting 
the candidates still agreed with the conception of choosing the 
speaker", he pointed out. He believes that the chairman of the 
State Duma will be elected on the second day of the session. 
Otherwise the process will become endless, Zerkaltsev stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

