<F P=100> Uzbekistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kazakh President Nazarbayev Arrives on Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001153294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1437 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001153294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vilor Niyazmatov] </F>
  [Text] Tashkent January 10 TASS -- Kazakhstan's President 
Nursultan Nazarbayev arrived in Tashkent on an official visit on 
Monday. His plane just landed in Tashkent airport. 
  This is his first trip to neighbouring Uzbekistan this year. 
In 1993 the leaders of the two republics held five such 
meetings in Tashkent, Almaty, Kokchetav, Kzyl Orda and Chimkent. 
  Those were not spontaneous or off-hand meetings. It is 
common knowledge that official contacts and the policy pursued 
by the two leaders who have already been recognised by the world 
will largely affect the situation in the entire Central Asian 
region. Each such meeting helps solve urgent economic and 
social problems and lay the foundation for building a common 
market in the region. 
  These issues will feature prominently during the talks 
between Nazarbayev and Uzbek leaders. The sides are expected to 
sign a package of documents which will bring the two countries 
even closer together and provide a basis for stronger 
cooperation. 
  It is symbolic that today's meeting between Nazarbayev and 
Uzbek President Islam Karimov has coincided with the first 
anniversary of the creation of the term "Central Asia" coined by 
the leaders of Kazakhstan and five Central Asian republics at 
their summit meeting in Tashkent last January. It was then that 
the Central-Asian-region notion was brought to life. Despite 
all economic hardships it has taken firm roots in the political 
lexicon. Although not all goals were fulfilled at that meeting, 
regional integration is beginning to take up real shape. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

