<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Christopher Letter Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS0701175194 Tallinn BNS in English 1612 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS0701175194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vilnius, Jan 07, BNS -- U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher expects the upcoming NATO summit in Brussels 
to make decisions on the establishment of essentially new 
cooperation between the alliance and East European countries. 
  Lithuanian Foreign Minister Povilas Gylys received a letter 
from Christopher this week, saying the Brussels summit would be 
a favorable possibility to start closer security cooperation 
between the alliance and the newly emerging democracies in 
Eastern Europe, including Lithuania, the Lithuanian Foreign 
Ministry said. 
  Christopher said the summit is likely announce that NATO 
will 
welcome new members in the future. The alliance's evolutionary 
expansion would preserve its strength, harmony among its members 
and its ability to act. 
  The secretary of state said the Partnership for Peace 
program 
offers Lithuania close practical cooperation with both military 
and political structures of NATO. The initiative would require 
serious military and political steps -- to observe international 
obligations, to guarantee civil control of the armed forces and 
to properly arrange the military budget. 
  Christopher expressed hope that Lithuania will support the 
Partnership for Peace program and will take an active part in it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

