<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Rejects Use of Russian Troops </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001131794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1136 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001131794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze dismissed the 
idea of using Russian troops to enforce law and order in 
Georgia. In a regular Monday radio interview he said that a 
country which cannot instill law and order on its own did not 
deserve independence. 
  This was his response to the statement made by parliament 
speaker Vakhtang Goguadze Sunday that law and order could not 
prevail in Georgia unless Russian troops were called in and 
Georgia entered the ruble zone. 
  Nevertheless, Shevardnadze admitted that there could be no 
law and order in Abkhazia and North Ossetia without Russian help. 
  Shevardnadze noted that entry into the ruble zone should be 
given serious thought. In his words, the introduction of a 
national currency in Georgia was an erroneous and premature 
action. "The state and every family had to pay dearly for 
this," he emphasized. 
  Shevardnadze said that during his visits to Turkey, France, 
and the U.S., and talks with the World Bank and the 
International Monetary Fund, he might seek advice of foreign 
statesmen on entry into the ruble zone. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

