<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Validity of Kiev Disarmament Accord in Doubt </TI></H3>
<H4>   Rukh Head: Kravchuk Cannot Sign Pact </H4>
<F P=102> LD1101145194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1202 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] "President Leonid Kravchuk has no authority to sign 
any interstate documents regarding nuclear disarmament," 
chairman of Ukraine's Popular Rukh, Vyacheslav Chernovil, 
declared in his interview with Interfax-Ukraine. 
  Chernovil also emphasized that "principles of Ukraine's 
nuclear policy were determined by parliament during the 
ratification of the START-I treaty with certain reservations." 
In Chernovil's words, "all leaders of the country, including the 
president, must adhere to this course." 
  "If Kravchuk signs an agreement on nuclear weapons during 
his meeting with Bill Clinton and Boris Yeltsin on January 14 in 
Moscow, it will have no juridical force," believes Chernovil. 
  Valentin Lemish, chairman of the parliamentary commission on 
defense and security, told journalists on Monday that the 
agreement to be signed by the three presidents in Moscow is 
subject for ratification by the Ukrainian parliament. According 
to Lemish, "if the agreement is in line with the parliament 
resolution on ratification of the START-I treaty, we shall have 
no questions." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

