<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Validity of Kiev Disarmament Accord in Doubt </TI></H3>
<H4>   Further Comments by Official </H4>
<F P=102> LD1101183294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1645 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101183294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] "I cannot say that a document for the U.S., 
Ukrainian and Russian presidents to sign in Moscow on January 14 
exists," Ukrainian Foreign Ministry's spokesman Yuriy Sergeyev 
told journalists in Kiev. 
  In his words, "the document, in particular guarantees of 
Ukraine's security, is being drafted." He added that if the 
document is not drafted before Friday, the Moscow meeting will 
be consultative." 
  According to Sergeyev, the brief meeting of the U.S. and 
Ukrainian presidents in Kiev on January 12 will concentrate on 
the bilateral relations. "Ukraine and the United States want to 
have balanced relations which should emphasize the economic 
rather than the military and political sphere," he explained. 
  Sergeyev also explained that all treaties and accords that 
the Ukrainian president would sign must be ratified by the 
country's parliament. 
  The Ukrainian Supreme Soviet ratified START I with numerous 
reservations. The treaty provides for withdrawal of nearly 
1500, or 16 percent, warheads and 176, or 42 percent, strategiic 
missiles from Ukraine. 
  Numerous national democratic deputies of the Ukrainian 
Supreme Soviet have criticized the president's intention to sign 
a nuclear disarmament treaty in Moscow. 

</TEXT>

