<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dniester Republic Asks for Russian Support </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101191294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1755 
GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101191294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [by ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Demidetskiy] </F>
  [Text] Chisinau, 11 Jan -- The Supreme Soviet of the 
unrecognized Dniester republic has today adopted an appeal to 
deputies of the Russian Federal Assembly, asking for support for 
the Dniester region and hoping for understanding of its 
proposals on the creation of a confederation in Moldova. In 
their message the Dniester deputies accuse the leadership of 
Moldova of "persistently not wanting to tackle the Dniester 
problem and pursuing a policy of endless veering between 
threats, military conflict, and political blackmail." If 
Chisinau does not want to "find a mutually- acceptable 
settlement" of the conflict, Tiraspol asks the Russian 
parliamentarians "to recognize the Dniester Moldavian republic 
as an independent and sovereign state friendly to Russia". The 
document also contains a request not to withdraw the Russian 
14th Army from the Dniester region. 
  Moldavian Parliament Deputy Chairman Victor Puscas told the 
ITAR- TASS correspondent that the appeal from the Tiraspol 
authorities to the Russian parliamentarians bore witness to the 
fact that they were unwilling and unable to settle the Dniester 
region problem around the negotiating table. "There can be no 
question of any confederation," he said. "The Dniester region 
problem can and should be resolved within the framework of a 
united Moldova by means of granting the left-bank districts 
special juridical status." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

