<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Monetary Union To Be Discussed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101175694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1728 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101175694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Stanislav Shushkevich, Chairman of the Belarussian 
Supreme Soviet, will leave for Moscow late on Tuesday to meet 
with Russian President Boris Yeltsin there. Officials in 
Shushkevich's headquarters told Interfax that the setting up of 
a monetary union of the two countries would be a major issue the 
two men will discuss. 
  Observers note that Shushkevich and Belarussian Prime 
Minister Vyacheslav Kebich have significant differences over the 
economic integration of the two countries. 
  Valery Tsepkalo, an adviser of the Supreme Soviiet chairman, 
told Interfax that Shushkevich largely shared the views of 
Stanislav Bogdankevich, Chairman of the National Bank of 
Belarus, who opposes the signing an agreement on the merger of 
the monetary systems in the form it was drafted by a bilateral 
ad hoc team of experts. 
  Valery Dashkevich, an advisor of the National Bank of 
Belarus 
(NBB) chairman, told Interfax that his chief "thinks that before 
a monetary union is established an agreement should be reached 
on common prices of fuels and basic raw commodities. ... If his 
view is ignored, the NBB chairman may resign." 
  According to Dashkevich, the NBB chairman will accompany 
Shushkevich to Moscow. 
  Asked by Interfax whether Shushkevich intended to coordinate 
with Yeltsin his position in talks with U.S. President Bill 
Clinton, Tsepkalo doubted the need in this because, in his view, 
"Belarus does not have differences with the U.S.A. or Russia." 

</TEXT>

