<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow City Duma Opens First Session 10 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001162794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1443 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001162794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The first official session of Moscow's Duma opened 
in the former building of the Mayor's office on New Arbat Street 
on Monday. The opening State Duma meeting will be held in the 
same premises on Tuesday. Taking part in today's session are 32 
of the 35 deputies, elected by Muscovites on December 12, 1993. 
  In his opening address, 61-year-old Vladimir Plotnikov, the 
Duma's elder, said that the main task today was to adopt a 
statute of Moscow, which will become "a constitution for Moscow 
as a constituent part of the Federation." He also voiced hope 
that the relatively small membership of the Duma would guarantee 
its cohesion. 
  On Monday, deputies will discuss procedural matters, elect a 
speaker, and hear a speech by Konstantin Buravlev, the first 
vice-premier of Moscow's Government, who will discuss social and 
economic development and the budget for Moscow this year, report 
about temporary working groups, and announce an agenda for the 
next Duma session, scheduled for January 19. 

</TEXT>

