<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Officials React to President's Speech </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1201103294 Tallinn ETA NEWS BULLETIN in English 0753 GMT 
12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS1201103294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn ETA NEWS BULLETIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From 12 January RAHVA HAAL, POSTIMEES, PAEVALEHT, </F>
HOMMIKULEHT, pp 2,3] 
  [Text] Wednesday, January 12 -- Prime Minister Mart Laar 
described the recent events as a crisis of power rather than of 
government, stressing that the coalition had remained firm. He 
added that the constitution is inadequately expressed and needs 
a number of additional laws to guarantee the actual balance of 
power. 
  Laar rejected the president's accusations of inopportune 
moment for the reshuffle. "I consider the change of ministers a 
significant factor guaranteeing Estonia's stability. 
Considering the hard times ahead, we should go on with a 
monolithic government which effectively cooperates with the 
parliament," he said. 
  The prime minister admitted that the presidential speech 
contained a number of correct critical points, but added that 
Meri had not expressed his criticism so directly at the previous 
meetings. Laar also stressed that the government had been 
paying "constant attention" to the infiltration of the Russian 
capital into Estonia. 
  "Fatherland" faction chairman Tiit Sinissaar described the 
accusations as surprising and questioned the arguments used by 
the president. Deputy faction chairman Kalle Jurgenson stressed 
that the "Fatherland" sees no reasons for the resignation of the 
prime minister. 
  "Fatherland" MP [member of parliament] Mart Nutt and 
Moderate 
Vello Saatpalu stressed that Estonia is a parliamentary state 
and the president exceeded his authority. Centrist Andra 
Veidemann described the situation and the presidential 
expression of no confidence to the prime minister as 
"interesting and unprecedented". Coalition Party MP Ulo Vooglaid 
expressed his surprise and delight at the president's frank and 
honest analysis of the critical problems. 

</TEXT>

