<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia, U.S. Ease Visa-Issuing Procedures </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1201114194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1010 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1201114194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Aleksandr Krylovich] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 12 TASS -- The Russian Foreign 
Ministry and the U.S. State Department have exchanged notes on 
the facilitation of the existing visa-issuing procedures, the 
Consular Department of the Russian Foreign Ministry reported 
today. 
  The exchange of notes came as a result of the implementation 
of agreements concluded at the Russo-American summit in 
Vancouver last April. It is intended to officially assert the 
high level of mutual understanding between Russia and the United 
states in the sphere of consular relations, to systematise and 
facilitate to the maximum all the visa formalities, and also to 
eliminate obsolete provisions which are ineffective and 
contradict the current spirit of cooperation. 
  The agreement is based on the principle of issuing multiple 
visas for terms ranging from one to two years to a considerable 
share of the citizens of both countries. This refers primarily 
to participants of various exchanges in the sphere of science 
and education, officials of joint Russo-American organisations, 
companies and banks, businessmen, and also certain categories of 
officials of state institutions, making official trips. 
  This agreement, which will take effect as of January 15, 
1994, cogs in with the relations of partnership and cooperation, 
typical for current Russo-American relations, and pursues the 
purpose of further promoting political, commercial, economic, 
scientific, and technological cooperation, expanding contacts 
among people and between the public organisations of the Russian 
Federation and the United States, the report of the Russian 
Foreign Ministry's Consular Department notes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

