<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `No Danger' of Incursion Into Latvia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101173894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1645 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101173894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] There was no danger of an incursion by Russian 
troops into Latvia in connection with the arrest of two Russian 
generals there, Deputy Foreign Minister Sergey Krylov told 
INTERFAX on Tuesday [11 January]. 
  The Russian troops stationed in Latvia went on higher alert 
in connection with the incident, but they neither left the 
places of their deployment nor launched any aggressive actions, 
he pointed out. 
  As INTERFAX already reported, Monday morning groups of armed 
Latvian militiamen seized several installations belonging to the 
North-Western Group of Russian Troops. The two Russian generals 
who came to the locality were arrested on instruction from the 
head of the administration of a Riga district. Only when 
President Guntis Ulmanis intervened and presented his apologies, 
the Russian generals were released and the invaded installations 
were freed. 
  According to Krylov, this "gross and unprecedented action 
was 
probably designed to provoke Russia to take retaliatory 
measures." "The saddest thing is that it was launched at a time 
when progress was being made at the Russian-Latvian talks in 
Riga in regard to the key aspects concerning the withdrawal of 
Russian troops from Latvia," he noted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

