<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Skrunda Radar Withdrawal Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101192994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1732 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101192994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russia is ready to reduce the term of the temporary 
operation of its early warning radar station in Skrunda, Latvia 
from 6 to 5 years. This was reported to Interfax on Tuesday [11 
January] by the head of the Russian delegation to a Riga 
conference of Russian and Latvian officials Sergey Zotov. He 
said the Latvian side was offered a new Russian draft agreement 
on the temporary status of the strategic facility. He stressed 
that the indicates Russia is trying to meet the Latvian side 
halfway. 
  As we have reported one of Russia's conditions for the 
withdrawal of its remaining 13,000 troops by August 31 is the 
right to control the radar station in Skrunda for several years. 
Latvia has agreed to that in principle, but finds it necessary 
to reduce the length of this period. 
  The conference in Riga is expected to continue on Wednesday 
and the discussion of the draft agreement on the radar station 
to continue during the coming round of talks in Moscow later 
this month. 
  Sergey Zotov described the Monday incident involving the 
Russian military and Russian army facilities as a crude 
provocation of extremist and nationalist forces aimed at 
torpedoing bilateral talks as well as a test of Russia's force, 
its ability to protect its facilities. 
  Zotov thinks the incident should prompt the West to conclude 
that Latvia is an unreliable partner. 
  Before the meeting Sergey Zotov protested against the 
incident to the head of the Latvian delegation Martins Virsis 
and demanded a full investigation of thee incident and 
punishment for those responsible. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55836 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov008_a_94026" </HT>


