<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reinforcements Arrive in Serbian Krajina </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101184494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1037 
GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101184494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Aleksandr Kondrashov] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, 11 Jan -- The first of two trains with 
reinforcements for the personnel and combat hardware of the 
Russian "blue berets" battalion deployed in Serbian Krajina 
arrived today at the railway station of the town of Subotica. 
After the unloading of the hardware the detachment of Russian 
paratroops will go to the site of their deployment -- the 
"Klisa" airfield near Osijek. 
  In the next few days the 900 soldiers and officers of the 
"Rusbat," which is guarding a 100-km stretch of the line 
separating the Serbs and Croats, will be reinforced by more than 
300 extra Russian "blue berets." In addition to this 
reinforcement of personnel the battalion will have at its 
disposal several new armored carriers, anti-tank weapons and 
grenade launchers. The command calculates that this 
reinforcement will make it possible to lower the excessive load 
on the personnel who are manning 32 check- points around the 
clock. Meanwhile, the additional combat hardware will help to 
enhance the security of the Russian paratroops and forestall 
possible provocations and attacks. Incidentally, the Belgian 
battalion deployed in the same sector has already been equipped 
with the same types of weapons, while some national contingents 
of the UN forces even have tanks. 
  The situation in the zone for which the Russian battalion is 
responsible has become substantially more stable in recent 
months. This is explained not only by a certain easing of 
Serb-Croat relations but also by the skillful execution of their 
duties by the Russian soldiers and officers, constant contacts 
with the opposing sides, and efforts to prevent incidents. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

