<H3> <TI>   Karabakh Conflict May Internationalize </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1101115594 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 11 Jan 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM1101115594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Kirill Petrov:"Karabakh Front Has Never Before </F>
Been So Broad, Threat of the Conflict's Internationalization Has 
Never Before Been So Real"] 
  [Excerpts] In the morning of 9 January, following a 
relative lull, the Azerbaijani Army, supported by armored 
equipment and aviation, launched a fresh offensive in 
Mardakertskiy Rayon. Fierce fighting is under way, the sides are 
suffering major losses. [passage omitted] 
  The real threat of the conflict's internationalization is 
another noteworthy aspect. It is, alas, an open secret that 
envoys from Azerbaijan and the Nagorno-Karabakh Republic [NKR] 
are spending big money to hire "soldiers of fortune" in Russia, 
in Ukraine, in Belarus, in the Baltic countries.... 
"International aid" to the warring sides is already arriving 
from beyond the former USSR's borders. Afghan mojahedin are 
fighting on Azerbaijan's side. Furthermore, the notorious 
Hekmatyar and General Dustum have examined the possibility of 
rendering more effective assistance to Baku. Mercenaries from 
Lebanon, Syria, and other Near East countries are fighting in 
Nagorno-Karabakh's defense detachments. Teheran and Istanbul 
are finding it increasingly hard to conceal their annoyance with 
the development of events in the NKR. And even though these two 
capitals issue assurances of readiness to perform a peacemaking 
mission in the region, it is no secret that certain quite 
influential forces in both Iran and Turkey are also considering 
strongarm options of "international aid." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

