<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation Council Session Adopts Agenda </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101183094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1513 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101183094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] During the morning session of the Federation 
Council, the deputies adopted the agenda and rules of work. 
There are four items on the agenda: the election of working 
bodies, the rules of the first session, the election of chairman 
of the Federation Council, and the election of vice chairmen. 
  The majority of the deputies demanded that the government 
present a report because they believe that it does not know the 
economic and social situation in the country. Following 
debates, the decision was taken to ask Prime Minister 
Chernomyrdin or some other leading Cabinet member to address the 
Federation Council. 
  The rules of the session consist of 14 articles. If the 
session is attended by two-thirds of the elected deputies (114), 
the session shall be considered legitimate. One of the articles 
defines the duties of the chairperson. During sessions he shall 
have no right to comment on the deputies' speeches. Another 
article says that the Federation Council's chairman and vice 
chairmen shall be elected during a secret ballot. Each 
candidacy to the post of vice chairman shall be discussed and a 
separate vote shall be held on it. 
  After a break, at about 16:00, the working bodies of the 
Federation Council's session will be elected, and debates will 
be held on the election of the Federation Council's chairman and 
vice chairmen. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55873 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov008_c_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-008 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation Council Split on Regional Factions Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101184094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1741 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101184094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anna Melnikova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 11 TASS -- Territorial associations 
in the Federation Council will pose a threat to interaction of 
the legislative and executive authorities, North Ossetian 
parliament head Akhsarbek Galazov told ITAR-TASS here today. 
  A major task of the parliament upper chamber is the 
provision 
of efficient interaction between the State Duma, presidential 
structures, the government and regions. The chamber should 
"connect Russian federal power bodies with the authorities of 
territories, regions and republics," he said. 
  In his turn, Eduard Rossel, staunch advocate of the idea of 
the Urals republic and president of the association of economic 
interaction of Urals regions and republics, voiced the 
expediency of territorial associations in the Federation Council. 
  In his opinion, they should set up "regional parliament 
centers to unite local representatives of the State Duma and the 
Federation Council". He said the Urals association has been set 
up to include two republics and six regions. 
  Rossel noted they have not held consultations with other 
regions on the creation of similar "parliament centers", but it 
is planned to hold a conference of representatives of all 
Russian economic associations in February to continue the 
creation of similar associations on their basis. 
  Yuriy Boldyrev, a leader of the Yavlinskiy-Boldyrev-Lukin 
bloc, noted territorial factions will inevitably appear in the 
Federation Council due to different interests of republics, 
territories and autonomous formations and different political 
outlook. 
  Some deputies sharply criticize the idea of territorial 
associations. Nizhniy Novgorod regional governor Boris Nemtsov 
said they "pose greater threat than political factions in the 
Federation Council". In his opinion, territorial associations 
will deteriorate differences between various Russian regions. 
  Vladimir Shumeyko is negative about the associations. 
According to the constitution, the Federation Council shall be 
formed with representatives of executive and representative 
authorities of federation subjects and "it can include no 
factions or associations", he said. 
  According to Shumeyko, the upper chamber should think of the 
way legislation is applied throughout the Russian Federation and 
the influence of laws on the fate of regions. Members of the 
Federation Council should be responsible people, almost 
"senators," stressed Shumeyko. 
  Chairman of the Central Electoral Commission Nikolay Ryabov 
stressed the danger of territorial associations. In his 
opinion, federation subjects can settle their differences 
through compromises and cited as an example the proposal of 
Viktor Stepanov to nominate deputies from republics, regions and 
autonomous districts deputies of the Federation Council chairman. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

