<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Aide Expects Confrontation With Parliament </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101144594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1202 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101144594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Russian president's press secretary, Vyacheslav 
Kostikov, told journalists that Boris Yeltsin had fears about 
the work of the new parliament, but pinned great hopes on it. 
He also said that the information about consultations in the 
parliamentary factions suggests that the work of the new 
parliament, above all the State Duma, would not be easy. 
  "Confrontational moods may triumph," he said. He noted, 
however, that the new Constitution gave the president enough 
powers to prevent revenging forces in the parliament from fully 
expressing themselves. 
  Kostikov told Interfax that the president's attitude to both 
chambers was positive. "Yeltsin is the president of all Russian 
citizens and respects the choice of the nation, however 
contradictory it might be," he said. 

</TEXT>

