<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Upper Chamber Speaker To Be Elected by Secret Ballot </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101164294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1453 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101164294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 11 TASS -- The Federation Council's 
Credentials Committee, which was elected today at the first 
meeting of the new Russian parliament's upper chamber, 
recognized the powers of all 171 deputies elected to the 
Federation Council of the first convocation. Under the 
Constitution, the Federation Council is to consist of 178 
lawmakers, however the ballot in Tatarstan and the Chelyabinsk 
region was declared invalid and new elections are to be called 
there, Chechnya did not hold parliamentary elections at all, and 
one deputy only has been elected in the Yamal-Nenets autonomous 
district so far. 
  After their rights were confirmed, the lawmakers elected 
working bodies of the first meeting -- a secretariat, a 
vote-counting commission which is to count the votes until the 
conference hall is computerized, and an editing commission. 
  Then the deputies passed on to discuss a procedure for the 
Federation Council's first meeting. The discussion was quite 
calm and short. Even the item on a procedure for electing the 
upper house speaker did not provoke heated debates, although the 
vote itself is likely to become the most acute and difficult 
event at the meeting. The gathering agreed that candidatures 
for the post of chairman are to be nominated by deputies by 
secret ballot. Only one name can be written on the ballot. To 
become the Federation Council chairman, a deputy must poll over 
half the total votes. A special reservation stipulates that the 
speaker and his deputies cannot represent one and the same 
subject of the Federation. 
  When discussing the issue of "notorious quorum" and keeping 
in mind the constant lack of it at sessions of the former 
Supreme Soviet legislature, the lawmakers ruled that "a meeting 
is regarded as having legal powers if the attendance is no less 
than two thirds of the elected deputies". 

</TEXT>

