<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko Leads 4 Candidates for Upper Chamber Speaker </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101171494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1645 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101171494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 11 TASS -- Four out of 17 candidates 
will run on Wednesday for the post of the speaker of the upper 
chamber of the Russian parliament, the Federation Council, and 
First Deputy Prime Minister Vladimir Shumeyko is clearly in the 
lead. 
  On Tuesday 78 deputies nominated Shumeyko for the post and 
he 
needs 86 votes to become the speaker, a half plus one vote of 
171 registered members of the upper chamber. 
  The other three candidates are far behind Shumeyko. Petr 
Romanov, director of a plant in the Siberian city of 
Krasnoyarsk, was nominated by 13 lawmakers, Eduard Rossel, 
former head of the Sverdlovsk region and a staunch advocate of 
the Ural republic idea, got 10 votes, while former Industry 
Minister Aleksandr Titkin - 6. 
  Shumeyko told TASS that he would not quit the race even if 
lawmakers insist on that. "I do not intend to withdraw my 
candidature even if I am offered to", he said. 

</TEXT>

