<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation Council Discussing Election of Speaker </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1201113294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1036 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1201113294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 12 TASS -- The second day of the 
Federation Council's session began today with the discussion of 
candidates to the post of speaker of this higher chamber of the 
new Russian parliament. There are four candidates -- Pyotr 
Romanov, director-general of a Krasnoyarsk production society, 
Eduard Rossel, former head of the Sverdlovsk Regional 
Administration and currently president of the association for 
the Ural Region's economic interaction, Aleksandr Titkin, former 
minister of industry and currently president of a 
financial-investment company, and Vladimir Shumeyko, first 
vice-premier of the Russian Government. 
  The secret nomination of candidates, held the day before, 
showed that Shumeyko is an absolute leader. Seventy-eight out 
of the 161 deputies, who took part in the nomination, entered 
his name in the voting ballot. Thirteen deputies backed 
Romanov, 10 -- Rossel, and six -- Titkin. The number of 
nominated candidates reached seventeen, but the rest preferred 
to withdraw their candidatures. 
  A secret vote to elect the speaker will be held today at the 
morning meeting, after the candidates take the floor and are 
discussed. 
  According to the procedural rules of the first council 
session, adopted on Tuesday, "a candidate will be deemed 
elected, if he polls more than fifty per cent of the votes of 
elected members of the council as a result of a secret vote". 

</TEXT>

