<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Conflict Ensues Over Chairman of Duma Session </TI></H3>
<H4>   Lukava's `Bias' Cited </H4>
<F P=102> LD1101164794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1350 
GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101164794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Itar-Tass correspondent Lyudmila Aleksandrova] </F>
  [Excerpts] Moscow, 11 Jan -- Deputies from democratic 
factions are dissatisfied with the way the State Duma began its 
work, mainly due to the inexperience of an LDPR [Liberal 
Democratic party of Russia] member Georgiy Lukava, who is 
chairing the session, and his clear bias toward some parties. 
They believe that the establishment of a 50-seat minimum during 
the formation of factions will lead to the centrist parties 
being defeated and to the opposition playing a domineering role 
in the parliament. 
  The sitting of the State Duma, which opened at Moscow's 
Mayoralty this morning, focused on the struggle around the 
establishment of the minimum number of seats in a faction. 
While representatives of democratic groups favour a 20- or even 
a 14-seat minimum, the LDPR, the Communist party, the Agrarian 
party, and the Democratic Party of Russia advocate the 
introduction of a 50-seat minimum. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

