<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Reaches Compromise on Faction Strength </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101173094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1612 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101173094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 11 TASS -- After heated debate the 
Russian State Duma reached on Tuesday [11 January] a compromise 
on the first issue it had to solve -- the minimum number for 
lawmakers to be able to register as an official parliamentary 
group. 
  The compromise set the figure at 35. The opposition proposed 
50, while reformers insisted on 20. 
  Lawmaker Anatoliy Lukyanov, former Soviet parliament 
speaker, 
explained that the State Duma will consist of groups and 
factions which will enjoy equal rights. The minimum number of 
members for factions will be 14. This is the number of seats 
enjoyed by the Democratic Party of Russia which was the last 
among eight election blocs to overcome the five per cent hurdle 
in the December elections. 
  Another compromise was reached on the issue of the interim 
chairman. Several lawmakers called to replace Georgiy Lukava 
from the party of Vladimir Zhirinovskiy who they said is 
inexperienced in the job. 
  Now the session will be chaired by three oldest deputies in 
turn for two hours each -- Vladimir Bokov, Sergey Kovalev and 
Georgiy Lukava. 
  The Duma also elected Sergey Stankevich, the sacked 
presidential aide, to head the interim secretariat consisting of 
20 people. 
  Igor Bratishchev was elected head of the vote-counting 
commission while Grigoriy Bondarev became the chairman of the 
interim commission for procedural rules. 
  The interim secretariat will include five commissions -- for 
registration of deputies' associations, for organisation of the 
Duma sessions, for registration of deputies' proposals, for 
public relations, for work with proposals on Duma's schedule. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

