<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abkhazians Allow Repairs at Inguri Station </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101193694 Tbilisi CONTACT INFORMATION AGENCY in Russian 
1650 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101193694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi CONTACT INFORMATION AGENCY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] According to the state minister Givi Lominadze, the 
chairman of the temporary committee for emergencies in western 
Georgia, the region remains stable. The situation is calm if 
somewhat tense along the line of confrontation, which is marked 
by the Inguri River. The Abkhaz side has given permission for 
power engineers to cross the so-called border to carry out 
repair work at Inguri hydroelectric power station in Gali rayon. 
Units of the Georgian armed forces stationed in the region are 
guarding the area along the river Inguri. 
  The situation in Gali rayon in the border area remains 
critical as Abkhaz separatists and mercenaries from the northern 
Caucasus continue to rob civilians, burn houses, and kill people. 
  Under an accord between the Georgian and Abkhaz sides, 
between 25 and 30 people a day are granted passes and cross the 
road bridge over the Inguri from Zugdidi rayon into Gali rayon. 
However, according to reliable information, mines laid by 
Abkhaz separatists have killed over 60 people attempting to 
cross illegally. 

</TEXT>

