<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paramilitary Group To Stockpile Weapons </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101163694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1439 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101163694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [by ITAR-TASS correspsondent Albert Kochetkov] </F>
  [Text] Tbilisi January 11 TASS -- The command of the 
"Mkhedrioni" (Horsemen) Georgia's most powerful paramilitary 
organisation, nominally loyal to Eduard Shevardnadze, have 
decided to stockpile their firearms. 
  Longi Chelidze, a "Mkhedrioni" leader, told reporters on 
Tuesday that any member of the organisation refusing to obey the 
order to give up his weapon will be reported to the law 
enforcement bodies of the republic. 
  By January 15, all weapons should be collected and sealed in 
dumps. The operation has been already completed on Tuesday in 
the republic eastern regions of Kakheti and Rustavi. 
  Not long ago the "Mkhedrioni" units, playing a big role in 
the Georgian political drama, got the status of a governmental 
structure called "Georgia's Rescuers". 
  Local observers believe the "Mkhedrioni" leaders decided to 
get rid of weapons in a bid to evade any accusations of illegal 
activities against the members of the organisation. 
  The "Mkhedrioni" were founded in 1989 by Djaba Ioseliani, 
once a supporter of the late ex-president, Zviad Gamsakhurdia, 
who later inspired the downfall of the first popular-elected 
president of Georgia. 
  In November 1990, Ioseliani told ITAR-TASS That the 
"Mkhedrioni" had been created to prevent ethnic conflicts and 
preserve the republic's integrity. The "Horsemen" actively 
participated in the Georgian coup d'etat of December 
1991-January 1992, combat operations in Abkhazia and western 
Georgia on the side of the government troops. 
  Experts assess that "Mkhedrioni" consist of some three 
thousand well-equipped gunmen, possess armour and modern means 
of liaison. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55900 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov008_s_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-008 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ruble Zone Viewed as Nation's `Real Rescue' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101175594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1513 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101175594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vakhtang Goguadze, speaker of the Georgian 
parliament, declared the necessity of the republic to join the 
ruble zone. In his interview with INTERFAX he underlined that 
"it is necessary to raise this question as soon as possible." 
"I would like to see a strong Georgia which would be able to 
defend itself and a step towards the ruble zone is a chance for 
Georgia's real rescue," he emphasized. 
  Goguadze also declared that he positively assesses proposals 
of several political functionaries to introduce Russian forces 
into Georgia in order to bring order in the republic. At the 
same time, he noted that "this should be done minding genuine 
necessity." 
  Goguadze stated that cooperation with other countries "which 
would not restrict Georgia's sovereignty is always acceptable." 
  The speaker stressed the necessity to render assistance to 
Georgia's law enforcement bodies. "A policeman without money is 
a potential criminal and that is why we need help so we can 
bring order in the country," announced Goguadze. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

