<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Civilian Role Hinted at for Skrunda </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1201095394 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
2000 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PM1201095394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By A. Yakovlev and V. Gorobets; from the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] [Yakovlev] Russian-Latvian talks, overshadowed by 
the illegal arrest of two Russian generals, began this morning 
and carried on late into the evening. The Latvian delegation 
agreed to Russia's proposed date for the withdrawal of troops -- 
31 August this year. The only fundamental issue on which it has 
hitherto not been possible to agree is the Skrunda missile 
attack early-warning station. It is necessary to define the 
status of this strategic installation, needed to ensure Russia's 
national security, and establish the possibility of 
international supervision, something on which the Latvian side 
is insisting. The opinion is being aired that the station might 
operate as a civil installation. Military experts believe that 
the Skrunda radar does not represent an environmental danger nor 
does it pose a threat as a target on Latvian territory. 
Agreement is being hampered by the impossibility of putting up 
a similar structure on Russian territory in a short period and 
the internal situation in Latvia, which dictates that 
politicians should seek the immediate withdrawal of all troops 
and the elimination of Russian installations on its territory. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

