<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Interviews Ambassador </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1101124794 Vilnius ELTA NEWS BULLETIN in English 0814 GMT 
11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS1101124794 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius ELTA NEWS BULLETIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From ELTA "NEWS BULLETIN" No. 411] </F>
  [Text] Warsaw, Jan 10, ELTA -- "We are not so naive not to 
understand that after applying to NATO the door of the alliance 
would not immediately open. But as we belong to the West and 
not to the East, we want to get closer as soon as possible", 
Lithuanian ambassador at NATO Adolfas Venckus told a Polish 
daily "Rzeczpospolita" on Monday [10 January]. 
  Venckus said in the interview that the Baltic states were 
ready to give over one battalion to the European peacekeeping 
forces, were proposing centre of medical training, were ready to 
participate in NATO military exercises, paid a lot of attention 
to learning of foreign languages by senior military personnel. 
  "Our wish to join NATO is not directed against Russia. We 
would like to have the best possible relations with that country 
but some fears appeared after the elections in Russia and 
statements of Vladimir Zhirinovsky concerning the Baltic 
states", he said. 
  Asked how Lithuania would react if Poland was the first to 
join NATO, Venckus said that "Lithuania is not harmed by the 
success of others. But, if Poland offered the Baltic states to 
go to NATO together, we would be very happy". 
  Lithuania and Albania are the only states that have formally 
applied NATO for membership. 

</TEXT>

