<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Consider Meeting Mass Media Demands </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101190094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1757 GMT 11 Jan 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101190094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Ivanova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 11 TASS -- The working group headed 
by Russian First Deputy Prime Minister Vladimir Shumeyko drafted 
an ordinance by the cabinet of ministers on the mass media. The 
document provides for a three-month suspension of the order to 
revaluate the capital assets of enterprises and organizations in 
its part concerning printing-houses, TASS was told today at the 
Russian Journalists' Union. The sharp rise in printing expenses 
nearly provoked a one-week strike of newspapermen. 
  Furthermore, the draft ordinance instructs the relevant 
agencies to consider the possibility of granting the mass media 
the status of cultural institutions in order to reduce taxes 
collected from them. The document also suggests that the 
publishers of children's books and textbooks be exempted from 
taxes and that socially important publications be subsidized by 
the state. 
  The draft also calls for certain amendments to the 
privatization programme for this year with a view to take a 
proper account of the mass media. Some governmental agencies 
are also instructed to solve other concrete problems facing the 
press. 
  The document is expected to be considered within the next 
few 
days. The working group of its drafters, which was set up as a 
result of the recent meeting of newspaper editors-in-chief and 
heads of journalists' associations with Russian Prime Minister 
Viktor Chernomyrdin, includes head of the Russian Committee for 
the Press Boris Mironov, chairman of the Russian Journalists' 
Union Vsevolod Bogdanov, head of the Association of Publishers 
and Editors-in-Chief Ivan Laptev. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55936 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov008_b_94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-008 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sobchak Says KGB Set Up Zhirinovskiy Party </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1201094494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0724 
GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1201094494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, 12 Jan (ITAR-TASS) -- "I have reliable 
information known at present to very few people about how 
Zhirinovskiy's party was set up, St. Petersburg Mayor Anatoliy 
Sobchak said. It happened straight after the abolition of 
Article 6 in the Constitution of the day -- one that stipulated 
the CPSU's monopoly on power. 
  Today's issue of LITERATURNAYA GAZETA [LITERARY GAZETTE, a 
Moscow-based weekly] reports that Anatoliy Sobchak made this 
announcement during a ceremony at which he was presenting his 
new book, The Tbilisi Fracture, or Bloody Sunday 1989. 
  A multiparty system is in the offing, so we must act before 
the event, words to that effect were, according to the mayor, 
said by Mikhail Gorbachev at a Politburo sitting at the time. 
We ourselves ought to set up the first alternative party, but 
one that would be malleable. 
  The selection of a prospective party leader was left to the 
then-KGB, Sobchak says. As always, it rose to the task; it 
found among its so-called active reserve a man with the military 
rank of captain, whose name is now widely known. The name of 
the party, Liberal Democratic, was also invented there and then. 
It was a real success: After all, the word liberal has long 
been compromised in this country. Two weeks later the new party 
was officially registered. It was the first registered 
political party in the country, since the CPSU had never 
undergone the procedure; the party of Russian Communists was not 
registered until much later and under a slightly different name. 
  This story, the St. Petersburg mayor said, will be told in 
his next book, which is to be entitled: Once Upon a Time 
There Was a Communist Party. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

