<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Interior Troops Might Come Under Yeltsin </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101132694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1300 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101132694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Gondusov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 11 TASS -- The Russian interior 
troops may be subordinated directly to the president following 
the example of the former Security Ministry and the frontier 
troops, according to a planned reform of the Interior Ministry, 
TASS learned on tuesday from well-informed sources in the 
presidential administration which added, however, that no 
concept of reform had been yet submitted to the president. 
  The Interior Ministry will most probably be divided in 
several parts called "operative main departments" which will be 
entrusted with fighting the most serious types of crime. The 
departments will comprise criminal police. 
  Policemen who ensure public order may be united into 
municipal police. 
  Firemen and investigators will become "independent" 
departments, as well as the department which deals with prisons 
and labour camps. 
  The reform scheme is currently being drafted by the interior 
ministry itself, according to the sources. 
  Experts are split in assessing the planned reform of the 
Interior Ministry. Some of them told TASS they are against 
splitting the anti-crime forces while others believe the reform 
of the ministry is necessary to meet the demands of the time. 

</TEXT>

