<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Personnel Directorate To Be Cut </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM1101160894 Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA in Russian 11 Jan 
94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PM1101160894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Own Information" report carried as part of "Military </F>
Review" feature under the general heading "Everything Changes in 
the Army. Except the Defense Minister's Birthday":"Spare a Word 
for the Poor 'Glavpur' [Main Political Directorate]"] 
  [Text] The Defense Ministry collegium has made another 
decision on another reorganization of the Main Directorate for 
Work with Personnel, the now former the Main Military-Political 
Directorate of the Soviet Army and the Navy. Veteran political 
workers will remember that this is either the fourth or the 
fifth "purge" of the once indivisible ranks of ideologists and 
propagandists. The names, structures, and staffs have changed 
but the department itself has remained, albeit with fewer 
people. Everyone criticized it except the lazy ones: a "bastion 
of stagnation," a "hotbed of deception," and so forth. But in 
the crackle of newspaper crossfire it seemed to have been 
forgotten that there is no other organization capable of taking 
care of the education of soldiers and sailors. There was much 
talk about military chaplains but for some reason priests, 
mullahs, and rabbis did not appear in the barracks. 
  "The army is outside politics" -- that was the main slogan 
of 
recent years. But can that be said today after the events of 4 
October and the elections? Some observers, albeit highly 
cautious ones, connect the latest "purge" of the "Glavpur" with 
the elections in particular. In Russia's political elite people 
believe that the Army made a weighty contribution to Vladimir 
Volfovich [Zhirinovskiy]'s victory. But it voted for the new 
Constitution, too, didn't it? 
  Be that as it may, it is now being said that the 
directorate's staffs will be reduced by two-thirds leaving fewer 
than 50 people in the new structure. What will the trade-off 
be? For the moment there is none. The Armed Forces will 
finally be outside politics and at the same time outside 
education. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

