<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meri Explains Reasons for Government Reshuffle </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101135994 Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network in Estonian 0815 
GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101135994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Estonian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Speech by President Lennart Meri to the Riigikogu -- live] </F>
  [Excerpts] [Meri] [passage omitted] Instead of drawing 
objective conclusions from the changing balance of power in both 
the world and in Estonia, and expanding the governmental basis 
resolutely -- if necessary at the cost of his own resignation -- 
the prime minister has aimed at preserving his power and making 
a dangerous compromise. 
  The proposed government reshuffle will retain current 
governmental practices and the current decision-making 
mechanism, which works behind closed doors in a room next door 
rather than around the governmental table. The outcome is a 
more administrative government with a more administrative prime 
minister. Concentrating power instead of delegating it cannot 
be served up as a parliamentary practice, however attractively 
arranged. The reason why I consider it necessary to talk to 
you, esteemed people's deputies, with worry and openness, stems 
from an issue that a year or two ago was not yet topical. It is 
topical today and directly concerns Estonian national security. 
I say this as the top commander of Estonian state defense 
according to Section 16, Article 78 of the Constitution. 
[passage omitted] 
  Having said what I had to say and hoping that at critical 
moments the country's interests would come higher than party 
interests, I will now, before your very eyes, sign the 
resolution, which at the present moment in history must unite 
us, lift us above our differences of opinion, and assist the 
republican government in keeping the Estonian country's 
interests apart from party interests. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

