<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Comments on Outcome of NATO Summit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101195394 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1800 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101195394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Foreign Minister Andrey Vladimirovich </F>
Kozyrev by correspondent Vladimir Beletskiy; place and date not 
given; from the "Novosti" newscast -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Beletskiy] Andrey Vladimirovich, what is your 
comment on the results of the NATO conference in Brussels? 
  [Kozyrev] It took a step in the right direction; that is, 
the idea of Partnership for Peace has been approved, something 
which essentially is based also on our proposals. The effect is 
that now, instead of a quantitative membership expansion of NATO 
eastward, one should be occupied with the practical aspects of 
interaction, both between Russia and NATO, and between the 
Central European states and NATO, within the context, say, of 
joint maneuvers, practicing peacekeeping operations in areas of 
conflicts, programs of converting military production. This is 
practical work instead of membership. 
  Of course, there is a small difference of emphasis. NATO 
looks at things from its own viewpoint [NATO smotrit ot sebya] 
-- NATO-centrism--and they say this will be a period of 
preparation for joining NATO. Perhaps that will be the case. 
Let us see at the end of this period, which will be a fairly 
long and eventful one. It is perfectly possible that Russia 
will also decide, in the end, to join NATO. 
  Another scenario is possible, that NATO will be modified and 
merged into some broader European structure. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

