<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karabakh Repels Azeri Airborne Attack </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1201150494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1415 
GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1201150494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vadim Byrkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 12 Jan -- After a long break, Azeri Air 
Force assault aircraft today again appeared in the skies above 
Stepanakert. The ITAR-TASS correspondent was told on the phone 
by the press service of the headquarters of the Nagorno-Karabakh 
Defense Army that in the afternoon, two assault aircraft tried 
to bomb Stepanakert, but after response actions by Karabakh 
antiaircraft forces, they were forced to leave the airspace of 
Nagorno-Karabakh. But today the Azeri forces' offensive on most 
sections of the front continued. 
  According to a report by the press service of the military 
department, on Tuesday evening [11 January], subunits of the 
Karabakh Defense Army repulsed all attacks and maneuvered 
successfully, managing to surround a group of the Azeri Army in 
the area of the village of Akop Kamari in the north of 
Mardakertskiy [Mardakert] Rayon. Forty-six Azeri soldiers were 
killed and control was reestablished over a number of heights 
previously seized by the enemy. In the course of repulsing the 
attacks on other sections of the front, three infantry companies 
(up to 270 men and officers) of the Azeri National Army were 
destroyed, mainly by well-aimed artillery fire. 
  The Karabakh side's losses amounted to six killed and 15 
wounded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

