<H3> <TI>   Commission Chairmen on Cooperation With NATO </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1301105294 Tallinn ETA NEWS BULLETIN in English 0800 GMT 
13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS1301105294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn ETA NEWS BULLETIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From 13 January RAHVA HAAL, p 1] </F>
  [Text] Thursday, January 13 -- "We cannot express our 
disappointment with the NATO summit. We have done too little to 
attract the interest of the NATO," head of the Riigikogu 
[parliament] defence commission Rein Helme said. 
  He added that Estonia has problems with regional cooperation 
and pointed out the border issues with Russia. Admission to the 
NATO is impossible in case of such problems, which will have to 
be either solved or frozen, Helme said. 
  As for the appeal of the Lithuanian president, Helme 
commented that consultations between parliaments and governments 
would have been necessary, since the issue concerns the entire 
nation. 
  The Riigikogu foreign affairs commission is waiting official 
documents from Brussels, commission chairman Vello Saatpalu 
said. Saatpalu expressed his amazement at Prime Minister Mart 
Laar's announcement that Estonia is ready to appeal to Brussels 
in the nearest future, complaining that the foreign affairs 
commission had again been excluded from the making of vital 
decisions. Saatpalu added that this and other incidents 
indicate a movement from the rule of law to a state of 
administration. 

</TEXT>

