<H3> <TI>   Moderates Hold News Conference on Cabinet Crisis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1301105894 Tallinn ETA NEWS BULLETIN in English 0800 GMT 
13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS1301105894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn ETA NEWS BULLETIN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From 13 January PAEVALEHT, p 1] </F>
  [Text] Thursday, January 13 -- The Moderate faction of the 
Riigikogu [parliament] held a news conference yesterday on the 
recent crisis around the appointment of ministers. 
  Rural Centrist Ivar Raig, Social Democrat Ardo Ojasalu and 
faction member Heiki Nestor claimed that President Lennart Meri 
is provided with false information. They explained their claim 
with the president's opposition to the replacement of former 
Economy Minister Toomas Sildmae. Raig claimed that the actual 
situation was exactly opposite to what Meri had said, stressing 
that the ministry had not submitted a single original draft law 
to the Riigikogu. He also rejected the president's accusations 
that the prime minister was building an administrative state. 
The presidential chancellery has placed the president in an 
unpleasant situation, he said. 
  Heiki Nestor claimed that economic circles are exerting 
pressure on the president, while Ardo Ojasalu regretted the 
descent "on the level of everyday politics". Raig added that 
Toomas Sildmae was the only winner in the conflict. 
  The Moderates also commented on the possibility of a breakup 
of their faction, claiming that an agreement had been achieved, 
according to which no breakup will take place in the nearest 
three months. This was done as a favour to the independent 
faction members who would have had to make their choice in a 
short time otherwise. 

</TEXT>

