<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paper Cites Officials on Upcoming Clinton Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Strobe Talbott Comments </H4>
<F P=102> PM1201122994 Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI in Russian 12 Jan 94 p 
3 </F>

<F P=103> PM1201122994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report under the general heading "Americans </F>
Talk About Russia: U.S. President Bill Clinton's Four-Day State 
Visit to Moscow Begins Today. In Connection With This Event We 
Are Publishing Comments on Russia by Well Known American 
Politicians and Public Figures"] 
  [Text] Strobe Talbott, special adviser to the U.S. 
secretary of state [title as published]: 
  We are encouraging forces seeking integration with the whole 
world. 
  An extremely important event for the whole world -- that is 
how Strobe Talbott, ambassador at large and special adviser to 
the U.S. secretary of state on the new independents states, 
described U.S. President Bill Clinton's forthcoming visit to 
Moscow. 
  Answering journalists' questions during a TV linkup 
organized 
by the USIA, he noted that during this visit President Clinton 
will confirm that the United States "intends to firmly maintain 
its leading position in the international effort to support 
reform in Russia." These transformation, in S. Talbott's words, 
"can be considered the most important event of the present day." 
  During the visit to Moscow President Clinton will also state 
that "Russia must have its own powerful voice" in determining 
how the "situation in the sphere of security in Europe and 
Eurasia in the post-cold war period" will work out. "If Russia 
continues its course of integration...and continues to pursue a 
policy based on respect for neighboring states and their 
sovereignty and independence it will be able to join in the 
process of integration and the expansion of NATO," S. Talbott 
noted. After touching on the question of the prospects of 
relations with Russia, S. Talbott remarked that the Clinton 
administration looks to the future with "great optimism" because 
"Russia has a strong president." "President Yeltsin was and 
remains the leader of the reform process," he stressed. "We are 
trying," S. Talbott added, "to encourage those forces in Russia 
which are actively striving to ensure that the country makes the 
transition from communism to integration with the rest of the 
world." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

