<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   President's May Conclude Uranium Agreement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1201154394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1450 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1201154394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Veronika Romanenkova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 12 TASS -- A contract to use highly 
enriched uranium, obtained from dismantled nuclear weapons in 
Russia, may be approved by the presidents of the Russian 
Federation and the United States during their summit in Moscow, 
experts of the Russian Ministry for Atomic Energy hope. 
  According to a document, signed last February, and the 
contract, which was discussed by representatives of the two 
countries in September, Russia is to process 500 tonnes of 
weapon uranium over a period of twenty years. This uranium, 
after proper treatment, will be delivered to the United States 
as fuel for that country's nuclear power plants in amounts worth 
twelve billion U.S. dollars. Russia will use the obtained money 
for switching its defence enterprises to civilian rails, 
enhancing the safety of its nuclear power plants, supporting 
fundamental sciences, and cleaning the environment in polluted 
areas. 
  Moreover, the Russian Ministry for Atomic Energy expects the 
participants of the summit to sign an agreement allocating 75 
million U.S. dollars to Russian organisations from the 
Nunn-Lugar Fund. They will be used to build storages for weapon 
plutonium. The point in question is an additional allocation of 
75 millions, preliminarily negotiated by the Russian Ministry 
for Atomic Energy and the U.S. Defence Department to pay for the 
work done by building organisations, to grant subsidies to the 
region, where the storages will be held, and also to finance 
social requirements. 
  Two such storages are to be built in Russia -- one in Tomsk 
region and the other in Chelyabinsk region. The Ministry for 
Atomic Energy is looking forward to U.S. assistance in the 
construction of one of these storages. The construction of the 
other one will be financed by Russia. 
  Russian specialists also believe that the presidents of the 
two countries will discuss the earlier signed agreements and 
will conclude other bilateral agreements on new areas of 
cooperation in using atomic energy for peaceful purposes. These 
areas include nuclear power sources for space vehicles, joint 
efforts of Russian and American weapon laboratories to develop 
more effective procedures and technological means for the system 
of the International Atomic Energy Agency's guarantees against 
the proliferation of nuclear weapons and technologies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-55991 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov009_a_94005" </HT>


