<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Duma Official on Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1201174594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1628 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1201174594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 12 TASS -- "The very fact of the U.S. 
President's visit to our country shows what place Russia has in 
the U.S. foreign policy plans and priorities," Sergey 
Stankevich, head of the temporary secretariat of the State Duma, 
said on Wednesday. 
  "A personal meeting between the presidents of the two 
countries after a new constitutional and political reality has 
emerged in Russia is very important," he said. 
  Stankevich believes that until recently the United States 
had 
supported the most radical variant of economic reform in Russia. 
However, the "October-December crisis" (October revolt and 
December 12 elections which he also considers as a crisis) has 
shown that such variant has clear-cut social limits. Judging by 
many statements of American officials, the United States is 
ready to introduce considerable changes in its relations with 
Russia and stop supporting radical reform based on shock 
therapy, he added. 
  Stankevich stressed that such corrections will constitute 
the 
subject of discussions during President Bill Clinton's upcoming 
visit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

