<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Official on Arrangements </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1201175694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1722 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1201175694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By CRIME-PRESS correspondent Sergey Oleynik] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 12 TASS -- "I am sure that Clinton's 
security will be fully taken care of while he is in Moscow", a 
Russian security official declared. 
  Indeed, three security agencies are ready to guard American 
President Bill Clinton during his visit to Russia: the Chief 
Security Department of the Russian Federation, the Russian 
Presidential Security Team, and the United States presidential 
Guard. The number of people who are going to be directly 
involved in the protection of Clinton, who arrives late 
Wednesday evening, will exceed several hundred, according to 
First Deputy Director of the Russian Security Department Yuriy 
Krapivin. 
  If one counted up the number of auxiliary people somehow 
involved in the massive security effort, the numbers would run 
into the thousands. According to Krapivin, the Russian Interior 
Ministry will secure the U.S. President's travel routes and the 
sites which are included in the programme of his visit. The 
interior troops will also protect the "Radisson Slawjanskaja" 
hotel where President Clinton is scheduled to stay. 
  The Russian Federal Counter-Espionage Service is responsible 
for up-to-the-minute information, including reports about 
possible extremist conspiracies and criminal activity in Moscow. 
Even the Russian Foreign Intelligence Service took part in 
preliminary steps to guarantee Clinton's complete security. 
  Krapivin said that an advance group from Clinton's personal 
guard, which arrived with their armored cars and weapons a week 
ago, worked out a plan of cooperation with their Russian 
colleagues. The group thoroughly scouted out the president's 
hotel and the sites of his visits. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

