<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Welcomes Clinton </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301072794 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 0614 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1301072794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Speech by President Boris Yeltsin at a welcoming ceremony </F>
for U.S. President Bill Clinton at the Kremlin in Moscow--live] 
  [Text] Esteemed Mr. President of the United States of 
America, it gives me great pleasure to welcome you as an honored 
guest of the Russian Federation. Your day is beginning in our 
famous and legendary St. George's Hall in the Grand Kremlin 
Palace, in which the names and historic deeds of our great 
ancestors are reflected. This setting does, as it were, provide 
the starting point for our talks. 
  I well remember our first meeting in Vancouver. I remember 
how we laid the foundations for a U.S.-Russian partnership and 
how personal friendship arose between us. I am sure that this 
is a basis for ensuring that the talks this time will be even 
more in- depth, more practical, and more global in nature. 
  I think that you will retain a good memory of people in 
Russia, of Muscovites, and that you will sense this fully in 
your meetings with people. Welcome to Russia. Welcome to 
Moscow. 

</TEXT>

