<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Presidents Discuss `Broad Range of Issues' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301091694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0903 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301091694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Ivan Ivanov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 13 TASS -- ITAR-TASS learnt from 
reliable sources on Thursday [13 January] that Russian and U.S. 
Presidents Boris Yeltsin and Bill Clinton discussed broad range 
of issues at the Kremlin's Green Hall in a narrow format. 
  The issues included results of the general elections in 
Russia on December 12, progress in Russian reforms as well as 
questions of strengthening international security and nuclear 
non-proliferation. 
  In this connection, the sides stressed the importance of 
Ukraine's readiness to sign, together with Russia and the United 
States, a document on the withdrawal of nuclear warheads from 
its territory. The document will be signed in Moscow on Friday. 
  The sides also discussed the situation with a Russian radar 
station in Latvia. 
  The two presidents made a short tour of the Moscow Kremlin 
after the first round of talks. 
  Following the tour, the talks will be resumed in a broader 
format. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

