<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Continue Kremlin Discussions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301101994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1008 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301101994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Ivan Ivanov and Gennadiy </F>
Talalayev] 
  [Text] Moscow January 13 ITAR-TASS -- Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin and U.S. Presiednt Bill Clinton after walking 
between buildings in the Kremlin during a short break in their 
discussions, returned to St. Catherine's Hall of the Grand 
Kremlin Palace where they were joined by other members of the 
two delegations for further discussions. 
  In opening the second session Boris Yeltsin expressed 
satisfaction with the first round of talks. "We discussed the 
situation in Russia after the elections to the Federal Assembly 
and the referendum on the new Constitution, we touched upon the 
political and economic developments and examined the situation 
in the United States, as well as a number of questions relating 
to bilateral relations", Yeltsin said. 
  The Russian delegation taking part in the second round of 
discussions includes Prime Minister Chernomyrdin, Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev, Finance Minister Boris Fedorov, and 
National Security Council Secretary Oleg Lobov. This points to 
the likely subjects of the discussion -- Russian-American 
economic cooperation and assistance to Russia's reforms. The 
economic and political situation and security in the 
Commonwealth of Independent States amd Europe are also likely to 
be discussed. 
  Bill Clinton is expected to dwell on the Partnership for 
Peace programme and to summarise the results of the NATO summit 
in Brussels. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

