<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Meets Christopher, Approves NATO Summit Results </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301105494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1012 
GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1301105494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Georgiy Shmelev, ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 13 Jan -- Russian Federation Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev met today with U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher in the yellow reception room of the Great 
Kremlin Palace. The heads of the foreign policy departments of 
the two states examined a package of Russian-American documents 
to be signed in the course of the visit to Moscow by the U.S. 
President. 
  Galina Sidorova, the Russian minister's political adviser, 
told an ITAR-TASS correspondent that three agreements have been 
made ready for signing: Air traffic; health and biomedical 
research cooperation; and cooperation in the area of studying 
the effects of radiation on people's health and on the 
environment. A memorandum of intentions and cooperation in the 
sphere of export controls is also ready for signing. A joint 
Russian-American statement on the Near East will also be adopted. 
  Galina Sidorova said that the Russian and the U.S. 
Presidents 
will sign the main document -- the Moscow Declaration. They 
will also issue a statement on human rights and a statement on 
nonproliferation of nuclear weapons. 
  Andrey Kozyrev and Warren Christopher focused especially on 
the examination of the results of the NATO summit meeting in 
Brussels, the range of issues concerning mutual relations with 
Ukraine, and the position of the two sides on the eve of the 
trilateral Russian- American-Ukrainian summit meeting on 14 
January, Galina Sidorova noted. The heads of the Russian and 
U.S. foreign policy departments discussed in detail the problems 
of achieving a settlement in Bosnia. 
  Andrey Kozyrev emphasized in the course of the conversation 
that "approval of the Partnership for Peace program was the key 
result of the NATO session in Brussels." The formula is 
completely to Russia's liking. Andrey Kozyrev stressed: "We 
understand it to mean a broad and equal cooperation among all 
the interested sides." 

</TEXT>

