<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Press Secretary on First Clinton-Yeltsin Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301115094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1127 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Ivan Ivanov and Gennadiy </F>
Talalayev] 
  [Text] Moscow January 13 TASS -- After the end of the first 
round of Russian-American summit talks, press secretary of the 
Russian president Vyacheslav Kostikov told journalists that, 
from the point of view of Russia, the meeting is taking place 
"in a new political situation for the first time since the 
adoption of the Russian Constitution." 
  "Russia has joined the club of constitutional democracies, 
and this cannot but influence the talks," Kostikov stressed. 
  "The role played by the great powers in the world will 
steadily grow," he believes. Kostikov reminded that the hope 
for stabilisation in the world, cherished by people quite 
recently, has not come true in a number of regions, speciically, 
Yugoslavia, the transcaucasian region and Latin America. He 
said "the world needs a strong new order, and Russia will play 
the role of a great power in it." 
  Speaking about the content of the first round of talks 
between Yeltsin and Clinton, Kostikov pointed out that "they 
began in an atmosphere of genuine partnership." In his opinion, 
both sides proceed from the assumption that nothing can be done 
in the world without Russia and the United States. 
  Kostikov said that during the first round of talks the sides 
discussed the problem of the correlation of power of the 
president and the parliament. Yeltsin told the U.S. President 
about the situation in the country after the December elections 
in Russia. They also mentioned the recent summit meeting of the 
NATO member states in Brussels. 
  Clinton set forth the main ideas of his "Partnership for 
Peace" initiative. According to Kostikov, the initiative is 
still little known in Russia. "So far it has been an attractive 
formula which should be thought over carefully and thoroughly," 
he said. 
  Kostikov said as well that the problem of a possible 
expansion of NATO was also mentioned during the first round of 
talks. Yeltsin and Clinton stated the need, as well as their 
intention, for promoting the elimination of all dividing lines 
in Europe. The two presidents discussed as well the 
implementation of the agreements, reached at the Tokyo summit 
meeting of the seven main industrially developed countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

