<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Council's Lobov Comments on Clinton Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301125194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1152 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301125194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Ivan Ivanov and Gennadiy </F>
Talalayev] 
  [Text] Moscow January 13 TASS -- The second session of the 
Yeltsin-Clinton summit today lasted longer than scheduled - more 
than ninety minutes instead of the appointed 70 minutes. 
  National Security Council Secretary Oleg Lobov, who took 
part 
in the discussions, said the session mainly centered around 
economic cooperation and U.S. assistance to Russian reform, 
including financing and closer contactes with the interantaional 
financial organisations. 
  According to Lobov, Yeltsin spoke in detail about positive 
shifts and stressed that a slackening of pace is out of the 
question. 
  Bill Clinton said the United States is set to render maximum 
support to Russian reform and said his country should extend 
more active support to Russia in the social sphere. 
  Discussions are scheduled to resume on Friday morning after 
the tripartite summit in which Yeltsin, Clinton and Ukrainian 
President Leonid Kravchuk will work towards "the historic 
agreement to make the world a safer place with fewer nuclear 
weapons". As Presdient Clinton put it on Thursday morning. 
  Later today, Clinton will join President Yeltsin for private 
dinner in Novo-Ogarevo, the Russian president's dacha. 

</TEXT>

