<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shcherbakov: Stimuli for Russian-U.S. Cooperation Needed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1201152594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1434 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1201152594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS corresondent Igor Galkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow January 12 TASS -- "No doubt, the visit of 
U.S. President Bill Clinton to Russia will strengthen political 
interaction between the two countries. One would like to hope 
it would also promote technical and economic cooperation", 
Vladimir Shcherbakov, president of the International Foundation 
for Assisting Privatisation and Foreign Investment, told 
ITAR-TASS. "It is wrong when potential of the two countries is 
used to one tenth of a per cent". 
  Shcherbakov expressed perplexity that COCOM restrictions on 
the granting of new technologies to Russia have not yet been 
lifted. "It is not easy for Russia to receive technologically 
perfect products from the United States. Russia needs such 
products for economic development, for market development. U.S. 
companies do not use sufficiently vast opportunities for 
investment in Russia that brings mutual advantage". 
  Shcherbakov said that his foundation and the Lemont Brothers 
firm secured a tender for a feasibility study for the 
development of the Moscow aviation junction. Considerable 
advantage is promised by a private telecommunications network in 
Russia that is being created by joint effort of the foundation 
and the U.S. Andrew company. 
  Shcherbakov said there are plans for joint utilisation of 
missile silos jointly with several U.S. companies. Large amount 
of equipment, valuable metals and materials remain during the 
elimination of strategic missiles in silos. All this will be 
extracted and used. 
  U.S. firms are offered to participate in the implementation 
of the Russian programme for the utilisation of radioactive 
waste from submarines that completed their service. "This 
problem is encountered by Russia and the United States and form 
the point of view of ecology by the whole world", he said. 
"Russian scientists are far advanced in the working out of the 
technology for the utilisation of radioactive waste. It is now 
for the Russian and U.S. Governments to finance the works", he 
said. 

</TEXT>

