<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Western Military Source' on DPRK Submarine Deal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1301003094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0012 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1301003094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, Jan. 12 (YONHAP) -- A foreign press report 
Wednesday [12 January] that Russia has signed a contract to sell 
four fox-trot class submarines to North Korea is "nearly 
accurate," a Western military source said. 
  The TOKYO SHIMBUN reported that North Korea had signed a 
contract with the Russian Far East-Pacific fleet headquarters to 
buy four fox-trot submarines in the Vladivostok naval yard. 
  The source said that a North Korean naval delegation visited 
the naval headquarters in Vladivostok last September. Another 
North Korean high-level naval delegation secretly visited Moscow 
in November, apparently in connection with the submarine 
purchase. 
  The source said he believes that the Russian Far 
East-Pacific 
fleet has recommended sale of the submarines to naval 
headquarters in Moscow. 
  The fox-trot class submarine is generally classified as an 
attack vessel and therefore, if Russia proceeds with the sale, 
Moscow will be reneging on its promise to South Korea that it 
would not offer any offensive weapons to North Korea, the source 
said. 
  President Boris Yeltsin, during his visit to South Korea in 
December 1992, had affirmed that Russia would never supply 
offensive weapons to North Korea. 
  North Korea was understood to have explained to Russia that 
it planned to buy the submarines and disassemble them to use 
scrap iron. But since the submarines are still in usuable 
shape, the North Korean explanation is unconvincing, the source 
said. 
  The price of the submarines and other conditions of the 
sales 
contract are being kept secret, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

