<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Briefs on Various Issues </TI></H3>
<H4>   Views NATO Cooperation </H4>
<F P=102> LD1201175894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1720 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1201175894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Aleksandr Krylovich and </F>
Vladimir Taranov] 
  [Text] Moscow January 12 TASS -- "The Partnership for 
Peace" plan approved by NATO leaders at the recent meeting in 
Brussels will be "attentively studied" in Russia with the focus 
laid on boosting relations with NATO, Russian Foreign Ministry 
Spokesman Grigory Karasin told a briefing on Wednesday. 
  He added that the plan is an alternative to the expansion of 
NATO which East European nations want to join. "An approach has 
been selected which is oriented towards the development of 
partnership relations and practical cooperation with all 
European CSCE member-states, including in the East of the 
continent, and which provides equal possibilities for all 
potential partners," Karasin said. 
  Russia plans to hold a detailed exchange of opinions with 
all 
European states on the results of the NATO meeting in Brussels 
in order "to determine the optimal ways of maintaining a truly 
pan-European cooperation in the field of stability and 
security," according to the spokesman who added that prospects 
of such cooperation will be discused during the Russian-U.S. 
summit. 
  Karasin however explained that "the Russian-U.S. dialogue on 
the issue has nothing in common with any separate agreements 
between the two powers." This is only a search for such 
instruments of strengthening the European stability which would 
reliably guarantee the interests of all European states without 
exclusions, regardless of their size, georgraphic situation, 
economic or military potential." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

